data.description: Event Description: Join us for a vibrant and immersive celebration of Saudi National Day at New York University! Immerse yourself in the rich tapestry of Saudi Arabian culture through an evening filled with traditional food, drink, clothing, decorations, and games. This event promises to be a delightful fusion of heritage and modernity, uniting students from diverse backgrounds to experience the heartwarming hospitality of Saudi Arabia. Event Highlights: Culinary Delights: Indulge your taste buds in an array of mouthwatering traditional Saudi dishes. Savor the flavors of kebabs, shawarma, mandi, kabsa, and a delectable selection of sweets like baklava and dates. Experience the essence of Saudi cuisine right here at NYU. Sip and Savor: Discover the art of Arabian coffee and tea. Enjoy the aromatic brews of Arabic coffee (Gahwa) and the soothing flavors of mint tea. These beverages have been cherished for generations and hold a special place in Saudi Arabian culture. Dress the Part: Don traditional Saudi attire, including elegant thobes and stunning abayas. We will have a dressing area where you can try on these exquisite garments and capture the moment with photos. Decor and Atmosphere: Immerse yourself in a visually stunning ambiance adorned with Saudi Arabian decorations and traditional motifs. The setting will transport you to the vibrant streets of Riyadh or the serene landscapes of the desert. Games and Entertainment: Challenge your friends to traditional Saudi games such as Al-Malha and Al-Madfaa. These fun and engaging activities will provide a glimpse into the playful spirit of Saudi Arabia. Cultural Exchange: Connect with fellow students and Saudi nationals, fostering cross-cultural friendships and gaining insights into the Kingdom's unique heritage. Date and Venue: Date: September 23rd Time: 5:00 PM - 9:00 PM Location: Kimmel Center Room 802 (SHORIN) Come celebrate Saudi National Day with us at NYU in Kimmel Center Room 802 (SHORIN), where culture, tradition, and community unite in a joyous celebration of Saudi Arabia. Don't miss this opportunity to experience the hospitality, flavors, and traditions of Saudi culture right here on campus. Whether you're a Saudi national or simply curious about this rich culture, everyone is welcome to join in the festivities. Mark your calendars, and we'll see you there!
data.name: Saudi National Day 2023

data.description: Join us for a day of purposeful community service at the NYC Wine and Food Festival! We're in search of enthusiastic volunteers to help with event set-up and provide essential general support, including tasks like ticketing, registration, guest assistance, people check-in, and vendor support.  The NYC Wine and Food Festival is not just any event - it's an opportunity to support the God's Love We Deliver organization (GLWD). GLWD is a non-sectarian charity with a powerful mission: to provide nourishing, high-quality meals to individuals battling serious illnesses such as HIV/AIDS and cancer. Their dedication to improving the health and well-being of these individuals through delicious meals is truly heartwarming. when you volunteer at this event, you become a direct contributor to GLWD's inspiring mission. Your efforts will ensure the Festival runs smoothly, and providing attendees with an unforgettable and fun experience, all while raising crucial funds for this remarkable organization. Sign up to Taste the Joy of Volunteering and be a part of something truly meaningful. ** Note: All volunteers must be aged 21 and over. There are 2 shifts: 8am-11am Set-Up Team & 11am-4pm Event Support Team. Sign-up by 09/30/2023. **

data.description: For its first event of the semester, the bioethics interest group will be hosting a panel with several bioethicists from NYU Langone. This event is open to all students, regardless of previous bioethics experience. Anyone interested in learning more is welcome to attend! Our panel will feature Dr. Catherine Constable, a medical ethics consultant at Tisch Hospital, Dr. Ariane Lewis, a member of the NYU Langone ethics committee, Dr. Tamar Schiff, a postdoctoral fellow in the Division of Medical Ethics in NYU Langone's Department of Population Health, and Brendan Parent (JD), who is the director of Transplant Ethics and Policy research in the Division of Medical Ethics. Our panelists will discuss topics such as what got them interested in bioethics, how they see the role of bioethics in the hospital, how they see bioethics playing out in medical education, and which areas of bioethics are most pertinent to their careers. Dinner will be provided for attendees.

data.description: Global Awards and Me (GA+ME) is an introductory and exploratory program series, designed to support students new to the world of scholarships, fellowships and undergraduate research or "high impact opportunities''. Demystifying processes and dispelling myths is the way to dismantle barriers to awards and engage all students.    Winning award opportunities isn’t only about a high GPA and leading the team. It’s also about what you contribute; your strengths and experiences with navigating challenges; demonstrating reflective development, evolving from one opportunity to prepare for the next. This workshop will help students evaluate their “toolbox” (i.e. collection of academic & professional work and personal interests/passions) to pinpoint unique expertise, identify areas for growth, and showcase well-rounded skill sets and accomplishments in an award application and the essays. All sessions of the series will be virtual, livestreamed and recorded via Zoom. All registrants will receive the Zoom link before the event.   Event Recordings: All Fall 2023 virtual Global Awards programming will be recorded, and the recordings will be shared in this folder (NYU login required).  Please allow 2-3 business days for the recording to be made available.    _________________________________________________________________________________________________________________ *Note on Accessibility: New York University and the NYU Office of Global Awards provide reasonable accommodations to students with disabilities.
